body: @rd16395p Thanks for filing this. Could you provide a command you used to create the experiment?

@harupy Sure! I followed the instructions here (https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/issues/158#issuecomment-405408994) and I also tried running a sample scikit learn code and within the ui itself. 

Thank you.

@rd16395p Thanks. Have you tried logging artifacts in that experiment like below?

```python
import mlflow

mlflow.set_experiment("your_experiment")

with mlflow.start_run():
    print(mlflow.get_artifact_uri())  # should print out a s3 bucket path
    mlflow.log_artifact("path/to/file")
```
@rd16395p Did you replace "your_experiment" with your experiment name?
@harupy Yes, and it shows on the mlflow ui that the experiment is in the s3 bucket, but when I look to the s3 bucket it does not show the files actually made, and still makes it locally.

@rd16395p Can you try this?

```python
import mlflow

expr_name = "new_experiment"  # create a new experiment (do not replace)
s3_bucket = "your_s3_bucket_uri"  # replace this value
mllfow.create_experiment(expr_name, s3_bucket)
mlflow.set_experiment(expr_name)

with mlflow.start_run():
    print(mlflow.get_artifact_uri())  # should print out an s3 bucket path
    
    # create a file to log
    with open("test.txt", "w") as f:
        f.write("test")

    mlflow.log_artifact("test.txt")
```

@harupy Yes! That logged it there, thank you! How can I show it on the mlflow ui now? And do I have to do the same steps when logging to a remote server with regards to setting the bucket location in the code above?

Thanks!
@rd16395p Can you launch the MLflow UI by running `mlflow ui`?
@harupy Should I not run the mlflow server first? I set the artifact root to the s3 bucket there too.
